{
  "ADUs": {
    "A1": {
      "text": "If the contrast in contemporary meta-ethics is between utilitarian and deontological conceptions of how the theory of morality should be formulated, the major figures in the history ofethics will be Kant and MilL.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "A2": {
      "text": "Although Kant does think that the moral worth of an action is determined by the agent8 intention, he is concerned with the intentions of real actions with determinate consequences, not simply with empty intentions that are never put to the test in action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A3": {
      "text": "Deontological theories may not start with theory of the good, but that does not mean Kant should have completely ignored the relation of morality and the good.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A4": {
      "text": "Kant's own understanding of the major alternatives to his view i6 different from ours, given our tendency to contrast him with Mill.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A5": {
      "text": "Too much stress on these formal procedures, however, has also distorted our perception of Kant'8 full theory of morality.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A6": {
      "text": "Hegel attacks Kantian morality in many of his writings, but instead of then stating a different moral theory, he goe8 on to discussion of gome other topic, for instance religion or the state.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "A7": {
      "text": "From the Hegelian's perspective on morality 88 geen from the more inclusive context of Sittlichkeit, social action that is al8o moral will not need to be analyzed in terms of Kant's metaphysical dualisms between reason and inclination, intentions and consequences; or the sensible and the intelligible realms",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A8": {
      "text": "Hegel's goal is not to replace Kants moral philosophy with another, competing moral philosophy, but to accept it, while recognizing its limitations; as a special case of a larger theory of social action",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A9": {
      "text": "Hegel thinks this operation is simply a way of presupposing the desired outcome. Abstraction breaks persons into atomic entities with atomic qualities, and loses their concrete unity",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "A10": {
      "text": "Hegel's own approach i8 to make hermeneutical variability more difficult (although not impossible) by spelling out in addition to the moral theory social and historical theory.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
